Subject: [PATCH] PWDefault::buildNG: skip origin/destination as ng-candidates

The current buildNG ranks the (k-1) nearest outgoing-arc neighbors of each
vertex i, ordered by `objective->extend(0, i, j, true)`. On instances where
i has an arc back to the origin or forward to the destination (the typical
SPPRC route start/end split), those terminal vertices can fall within the
k-1 cheapest j's. They then occupy a slot in `unreachable_ng[i]` even
though they cannot be the target of an intermediate revisit during search:
the origin has no incoming arcs from customers, the destination has no
outgoing arcs. Tracking them in the bitset is operationally inert but
costs one effective neighborhood slot per affected customer.

Skipping origin and destination in the candidate loop frees that slot for
a real customer-revisit guard, tightening the ng-relaxation at zero
search-time cost.

Reproducible difference (instance A-n62-k8-99, ng/set_size=8):
  before patch: customers 15 and 28 ng-sets contain the destination (62)
  after  patch: customers 15 and 28 ng-sets contain customers 36 and 20

Reported by the bgspprc-spprc team during a parity comparison; the same
two affected vertices and the same downstream LP-cost difference appear
across the SPPRC `.sppcc` instance set.

--- a/src/core/algorithms/dynamic_programming/PW_default/PW_default.cpp
+++ b/src/core/algorithms/dynamic_programming/PW_default/PW_default.cpp
@@ -394,10 +394,15 @@ void PWDefault::buildNG(){
     unreachable_ng.resize(problem->getNumNodes(), Bitset(problem->getNumNodes()));
     std::set<std::pair<int, int>> neighbors;

+    // Origin and destination are terminal in the search (no intermediate
+    // revisits possible) and tracking them only burns an ng-slot.
+    int origin = problem->getOrigin();
+    int destination = problem->getDestination();
+
     //Arc-cost based ordering (should take into account extension instead)
     int neighborhood_max_size = ng_size - 1; //To account for node i in the set
     for(int i = 0; i < problem->getNumNodes(); i++) {
         for(int j = 0; j < problem->getNumNodes(); j++)
-            if(problem->areNeighbors(i, j, true)) {
+            if(problem->areNeighbors(i, j, true) && j != origin && j != destination) {
                 if(neighbors.size() < neighborhood_max_size)
                     neighbors.insert(std::make_pair(objective->extend(0,i,j,true), j));
                 else if(objective->extend(0,i,j,true) < neighbors.rbegin()->first) {
